TITLE: Using LazyOpenStream for On-Demand File Operations in PHP
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to use LazyOpenStream to lazily read or write to a file that is opened only after an IO operation takes place. This optimizes resource usage by only opening files when needed.
SOURCE: https://github.com/opencart/opencart/blob/master/upload/system/storage/vendor/guzzlehttp/psr7/README.md#2025-04-19_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: php
CODE:
```
use GuzzleHttp\Psr7;

$stream = new Psr7\LazyOpenStream('/path/to/file', 'r');
// The file has not yet been opened...

echo $stream->read(10);
// The file is opened and read from only when needed.
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Creating a Function-Based Stream with FnStream in PHP
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to use FnStream to create stream implementations based on a hash of functions. This allows for easy testing and extension of streams without creating concrete classes.
SOURCE: https://github.com/opencart/opencart/blob/master/upload/system/storage/vendor/guzzlehttp/psr7/README.md#2025-04-19_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: php
CODE:
```
use GuzzleHttp\Psr7;

$stream = Psr7\Utils::streamFor('hi');
$fnStream = Psr7\FnStream::decorate($stream, [
    'rewind' => function () use ($stream) {
        echo 'About to rewind - ';
        $stream->rewind();
        echo 'rewound!';
    }
]);

$fnStream->rewind();
// Outputs: About to rewind - rewound!
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Reading Stream Subsets with LimitStream in PHP
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to use LimitStream to read a subset or slice of an existing stream. This is useful for breaking large files into smaller pieces, such as for Amazon S3's multipart upload API.
SOURCE: https://github.com/opencart/opencart/blob/master/upload/system/storage/vendor/guzzlehttp/psr7/README.md#2025-04-19_snippet_6

LANGUAGE: php
CODE:
```
use GuzzleHttp\Psr7;

$original = Psr7\Utils::streamFor(fopen('/tmp/test.txt', 'r+'));
echo $original->getSize();
// >>> 1048576

// Limit the size of the body to 1024 bytes and start reading from byte 2048
$stream = new Psr7\LimitStream($original, 1024, 2048);
echo $stream->getSize();
// >>> 1024
echo $stream->tell();
// >>> 0
```

